ce:section.ce:para:
In reaction zone, hydrogen reacts with oxygen and a mass of energy is generated. Meanwhile, due to excessive oxygen, the reaction C6H5COOH(g) + O2(g) → CO(g) + H2(g) + C(s) is generated. This is the source of free carbons. Compared with the GQDs prepared from the top-down method, more sp3 carbonates are generated as reactant intermediates during detonation because many reaction types under higher temperature and pressure are possible. According to C-J theory, the temperature and pressure of detonation chemistry reaction are higher than 1500 K and 3 MPa, which are more conducive to graphitization [26]. At the same time, a high temperature is in favor of numerous single-step monomolecular reactions including CH bond rupture and intramolecular rearrangements [41] while the high pressure assists the ordered arrangement of freshly formed CC and the growth of crystalline GQDs [15]. The PAHs are viewed as the key intermediate compounds during detonation [26] in GQDs formation. In comparison with BA, the PAHs have lower oxygen content and a larger sp2 conjugated plane. Therefore, it is believed that BAs go through a sequential deoxidized condensation and dehydrogenative planarization (DCDP) approach to form PAHs. In a result, the reaction of DCDP with a high rate occurs in reaction zone to generate a multitude of PAHs. However, PAHs that act as sp2 subdomains do not increase in size infinitely, citing the energy and stability conditions. When sp2 subdomains confined by hydroxyl or epoxy groups are composed by 10 benzene rings, the formation energies will reach to 1.82 eV OH−1. That implies that extremely larger subdomains relatively have difficulty in formation [42]. Every PAHs should have 7–9 benzene rings because PAHs possessing more than 9 benzene rings have difficulty in formation while PAHs containing less than 7 benzene rings fail to emit blue fluorescence by employing density functional theory (DFT) calculations [42, 43]. The C-J plane is the boundary of detonation reaction, where the detonation velocity reaches a maximum value and the temperature as well as pressure is stable [25]. The intermediate compounds of detonation are extremely plentiful in the C-J plane, and this gives rise to a series of collisions among PAHs, oxygen-containing functional groups and massive free carbons. The collisions make PAHs interconnect to a larger plane with oxygen-containing functional groups and sp3 carbonates. As the C-J plane moves forward, the pressure and temperature of the products region drop sharply [25]. At the moment, the particle sizes increase upon the further collision of the coalescing sp2 conjugated plane containing more PAHs. Oxygen-containing functional groups and CH bonds are formed on the surface as confirmed by XPS and FTIR analyses. The further collisions promote the accumulation of the particles mass, and subsequently they agglomerate into coagulation as the products of GQDs. Under the effect of gravity, more products precipitate the lower wall of detonation tube. The as-prepared single GQD includes less than 9 PAHs which serve as a major source of fluorescence because of the limitation by size as recorded by HRTEM. The reason of higher absolute PLQY can be explained that the obtained GQDs are made up of multiple sp2 subdomains dispersed in an insulating sp3 matrix. In addition, in products zone, a sharp drop in temperature and pressure makes the excess free carbons enter the graphite phase. Subsequently, through a mass of crosslinking and stacking, carbon microspheres (Fig. 7
                           ) as by-products are formed [10]. Due to the diameter of carbon microspheres over 30 nm, it is facile to separate CQDs within the range of 1.6–3.8 nm from the mixture by ultrafiltration purification, and most importantly, it is easy to adjust the detonation parameters to minimize the yield of by-product so that it has no effect on use. All the process mentioned above is shown in Fig. 8
                           .
